{"id":1175,"date":"2022-02-14T17:19:00","date_gmt":"2022-02-14T17:19:00","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/?p=1175"},"modified":"2022-02-14T10:24:58","modified_gmt":"2022-02-14T10:24:58","slug":"start-and-stop-services-and-configure-services-to-start-automatically-at-boot","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/?p=1175","title":{"rendered":"Start and stop services and configure services to start automatically at boot"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>We already went over something similar with <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/?p=919\">network services<\/a><\/strong>. I&#8217;ve already explained back than how to automatically start them at boot as well, so this is going to be just short summarize. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 id=\"start-enable-the-service\">Start\/Enable the service<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>To start the service, we simply type<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">systemctl start httpd<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>As the name suggest, this will only start the service, but it won\u2019t survive reboot. To make it so, it starts with the system we use enable<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">systemctl enable httpd<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>We can also combine these two commands, so we don\u2019t have to type so much (typing two whole sentences, Am I right?!)<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">systemctl --now enable httpd<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image is-style-default\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"867\" height=\"74\" src=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-190.png?resize=640%2C55&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-940\" srcset=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-190.png?w=867&amp;ssl=1 867w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-190.png?resize=300%2C26&amp;ssl=1 300w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-190.png?resize=768%2C66&amp;ssl=1 768w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-190.png?resize=24%2C2&amp;ssl=1 24w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-190.png?resize=36%2C3&amp;ssl=1 36w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-190.png?resize=48%2C4&amp;ssl=1 48w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<h3 id=\"stop-disable-the-service\">Stop\/Disable the service<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Same commands apply to opposite action which is stopping and disabling the service<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">systemctl stop httpd<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">systemctl disable httpd<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">systemctl --now disable httpd<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image is-style-default\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"621\" height=\"55\" src=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-191.png?resize=621%2C55&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-941\" srcset=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-191.png?w=621&amp;ssl=1 621w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-191.png?resize=300%2C27&amp;ssl=1 300w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-191.png?resize=24%2C2&amp;ssl=1 24w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-191.png?resize=36%2C3&amp;ssl=1 36w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-191.png?resize=48%2C4&amp;ssl=1 48w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 621px) 100vw, 621px\" \/><\/figure>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>We already went over something similar with network services. I&#8217;ve already explained back than how [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":1174,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"nf_dc_page":"","om_disable_all_campaigns":false,"_mi_skip_tracking":false},"categories":[219],"tags":[421,357,220,359,420,354,355,422],"jetpack_featured_media_url":"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/02\/rhsa-Deploy-configure-and-maintain-systems-1.png?fit=1280%2C720&ssl=1","_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1175"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=%2Fwp%2Fv2%2Fcomments&post=1175"}],"version-history":[{"count":2,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1175\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":1179,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts\/1175\/revisions\/1179"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/media\/1174"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/t